[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Written Evidence from the Housing Ombudsman [PHS0034][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I 
[normal]am grateful to you for giving me the opportunity to contribute to your committee's 
[normal]inquiries into complaints handling.
[normal]Before addressing the specific questions posed in your letter, I think it would be 
[normal]helpful to the work of your committee if I sketched ou
[normal]t some background information 
[normal]on the Housing Ombudsman.
[normal]Background to the Housing Ombudsman Service [bold]Jurisdiction:[bold]The statutory Housing Ombudsman was created by the Housing Act 1996 and 
[normal]commenced operating as such on 1 April 1997. The relevant provisions of the1996 Act were amended in the Housing and Regeneration Act of 2008 and, more 
[normal]significantly, in the Localism Act of 2011. The Housing Ombudsman is a corporation 
[normal]sole and operates unde
[normal]r a Scheme approved by the Secretary of State (of the 
[normal]DCLG).
[normal]I [bold]am the second statutory Housing Ombudsman and was appointed in 2001. Until 1 
[normal]April 2013 my jurisdiction covered private not-for-profit (or 'not-for-dividend') 
[normal]landlords who are required by the 
[normal]1996 Act to be members of my Scheme "for all his 
[normal]housing activities" and private for-profit landlords and managing agents who may 
[normal]chose to be members. Since 1 April 2013 all the retained stock owned or managed 
[normal]by Local Housing Authorities (LHAs) or by Arms
[normal] Length Management Organisations 
[normal](ALMOs) on their behalf has come within my jurisdiction. Leaseholders of all 
[normal]member landlords are protected by my Scheme; there are, for example, about 
[normal]300,000 leaseholders of LHAs and they, like leaseholders in the 'housin
[normal]g 
[normal]association' sector, do not fall into the definition of 'social housing' in the 2008 Act.
[normal]Since 1 April 2013, therefore, it would be possible to categorise the Housing 
[normal]Ombudsman Service as a 'hybrid', having jurisdiction in both the private and public
[normal] 
[normal]sectors. This is captured in our mission statement which is "impartial dispute 
[normal]resolution in rented housing".
[normal]There are now 5.1 million units and about 12.5 million people in my jurisdiction. My Service is funded by the private, for-profit and not-for-profit, landlords who pay £1.47 
[normal]per unit per annum and grant-in-aid from government of £847,000 for the LHA 
[normal]dimens
[normal]ion of my jurisdiction.
[normal]Localism act 2011:[bold]The Secretary of State chose my Service to be the single housing ombudsman in the 
[normal]Localism Act so that there would be a "common route of redress for housing tenants" and "consistency in the treatment of complaints
[normal]".
[normal]In 2011, the impact assessment which preceded the Bill stated that government policy was to:
[normal]"...provide a common route of redress for all complaints about the performance of social housing landlords by designating a single, specialist 
[normal]ombudsman for soc
[normal]ial housing. In April 2010 a new cross-domain regulatory system was brought into effect, ensuring that tenants of local authorities and 
[normal]housing associations can expect a broadly similar level of service from their 
[normal]landlord. Given the move 
[normal]to consistent standards across social housing, we 
[normal]now wish to put complaint handling on a more consistent footing 
[normal]by
[normal]designating
[normal] a single ombudsman for all complaints about social housing 
[normal]landlords. At the same time, we want to ensure that there continues 
[normal]to be 
[normal]a
[normal]high
[normal] quality ombudsman service for all social housing tenants and their 
[normal]representatives"
[normal]Designating my Service as the single housing ombudsman was the preferred option because of our "existing single focus on housing". The option of giving the ext
[normal]ended 
[normal]jurisdiction to the Local Government Ombudsmen was rejected as that would not 
[normal]have resulted in there being a single ombudsman "specialising" in complaints about 
[normal]landlords as their remit covers all Local Government services. This was consistent 
[normal]with g
[normal]overnment's intention to have a single ombudsman in the context of a single, 
[normal]cross-domain regulator where there were "common standards set by a single regulator" and where it would make little sense for complaints about landlord performance (including agai
[normal]nst the standards) to be considered by two different ombudsmen.
[normal]These changes in the Localism Act stemmed from the government's recent review of social housing regulation which concluded, among other things, that the system for 
[normal]managing social housing comp
[normal]laints should be changed in order to strengthen the 
[normal]role of locally elected representatives and tenant groups, and address a perceived democratic deficit in understanding of housing issues at the local level. The review 
[normal]recommended that a 'democratic filter' should be introduced so that in future tenants 
[normal]who had exhausted their landlord's complaints procedure would have to go through their local tenant panel, MP, or councillor, who, in turn, would seek to resolve the 
[normal]comp
[normal]laint before, if needed, referring the issue to the Ombudsman.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If there had not been changes to the Bill as it passed through the House of Lords 
[normal]complaints would only have reached me if one of these 'designated persons' had referred it on to me. If they had not, the grievance would have died where it stood 
[normal]and complainants would have been barred from bringing the issue to me. Their only, and remote
[normal], opportunity for redress would have been through the ballot box.
[normal]Changes in the Lords resulted in residents being given a much wider range of 
[normal]choices in terms of seeking resolution of their grievances if not satisfied at the 
[normal]conclusion of their landlords'
[normal] internal complaints procedures (ICPs).
[normal]Direct access to the Housing Ombudsman:[bold]In spite of clear provision to the contrary in the Localism Act, a myth has grown up 
[normal]that disputes cannot come to me until eight weeks have passed after completion of 
[normal]providers
[normal]' internal complaints procedures (ICPs). This is a misunderstanding of the 
[normal]Act and of my Scheme approved by the Secretary of State.
[normal]It is true that one choice would be to wait eight weeks and come straight to me but 
[normal]residents 
[normal]might decide instead to go to 
[normal]a designated person (any MP, a local 
[normal]councillor, or a designated tenant panel) and ask them to resolve the dispute. What is less commonly understood is that they may go to a designated person and ask 
[normal]them to refer their dispute to me immediately. The desig
[normal]nated person may agree to 
[normal]or reject the request but, provided that agreement or rejection is in writing or 
[normal]confirmed in writing, the matter could be with me the same day.
[normal]This means that all tenants of councils and of private, not-for-profit landlords may 
[normal]use the designated persons to achieve not only the 'dual track' access to me that was recommended by the Law Commission but also resolution of disputes by designated persons themselves. The choice lies with tenants depending on their 
[normal]needs and the outcomes
[normal] they are seeking. Their landlords are best placed to help them make the right choice.
[normal]Tenants of those for-profit landlords who have chosen to join my Scheme can still 
[normal]bring their disputes to me without having to decide whether or not to engage with 
[normal]desig
[normal]nated persons.
[normal]The crucial upshot of these provisions is, of course, that all residents and tenants in 
[normal]my jurisdiction may have immediate and direct access to my Service if they so wish.
[normal]Local dispute resolution:[bold]We have made changes to ensure that more resources are devoted to early, local resolution where that is appropriate and proportionate. One example of this is that I 
[normal]now have the power, at any time, to promote local resolution of a dispute between 
[normal]any landl
[normal]ord and any tenant in my jurisdiction by either referring the complaint back to the complainant and provider (and/or a designated person) or by providing them 
[normal]with assistance to resolve the dispute. Also, I may decide to suspend or not to 
[normal]progress an inves
[normal]tigation if I think there is opportunity to resolve the dispute locally. 
[normal]So, for instance, if a complainant refers a matter to me before completing an ICP, my
[normal] 
[normal]new power enables me to offer a solution to the parties there and then. Equa
[normal]lly, I 
[normal]may propose a form of local resolution in any of the circumstances described above.
[normal]Strategy reviews:[bold]In 2006 we carried out a fundamental review of our core process and people development practices. In consequence, performance against targets for the 
[normal]organisation improved yearly. The work that was then required to prepare for my 
[normal]extended jurisdiction amou
[normal]nted to the most far-reaching review of the Service since 
[normal]it came into being on 1 April 1997.
[normal]In order to support Parliament's intention that, where possible, complaints should be 
[normal]dealt with simply and quickly at local level and that an effective service i
[normal]s provided to 
[normal]those cases which are escalated to me we executed an ambitious change 
[normal]programme which linked into our strategic imperatives. We carried out a fundamental 
[normal]review of all aspects of the organisation with one of our most important priorities 
[normal]bein
[normal]g to re-align resources to focus on front-end delivery.
[normal]Our strategic aims for 2012-13 were delivered by means of a Transition Plan that 
[normal]identified and mapped specific, timed objectives and work-streams that:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clarified and defined the precise nature and 
[normal]extent of my new role;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Developed new policy regarding management processes and learning and 
[normal]knowledge-management in the context of my new jurisdiction;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reviewed governance to ensure appropriateness for a statutory ombudsman 
[normal]and his extended role and 
[normal]jurisdiction;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reviewed and amended the approved Scheme;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Re-engineered the core dispute resolution process;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Designed dispute resolution principles to be supported by learning delivery 
[normal]media.
[normal]In order to ensure that the internal structure of the organisation
[normal] would be fit for 
[normal]purpose we:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Deployed the right people in the right roles;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reduced the size and cost of the leadership team so that more resources 
[normal]were applied to front-end service delivery;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Re-configured our office space to ensure that it was suitable for the necessary 
[normal]expansion of the team;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Developed internal systems to run the Designated Tenant Panels Register (in 
[normal]accordance with a specific provision in the Localism Act);
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Developed a new we
[normal]bsite to meet the needs of all of our key stakeholders;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Applied our stakeholder management and communication strategy and plan 
[normal]as critical factors in the delivery of the overall strategy and the mitigation of 
[normal]risks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Housing Ombudsman's[bold] new role:[bold]My new, two-pronged, role is now stated succinctly in the introduction to my new 
[normal]Scheme that was approved by the Secretary of State in February 2013; it is to 
[normal]resolve disputes involving members of the Scheme, including making awards of 
[normal]compensat
[normal]ion or other remedies when appropriate, as well as to support effective 
[normal]landlord-tenant dispute resolution by others. This new, composite role is now 
[normal]reflected in the changes to our strategic outcomes, revisions to the Scheme which 
[normal]regulates the Service, t
[normal]he re-engineered core process, new Dispute Resolution 
[normal]Principles, new learning media, and a re-focussed stakeholder management 
[normal]strategy.
[normal]The first 'prong' of my role is clearly reflected in our mission statement (above). We 
[normal]aim to provide an escalated comp
[normal]laint-handling and dispute-resolution service which 
[normal]is trusted, valued, and respected because it is fair, independent, impartial (free of 
[normal]bias and prejudice), effective, efficient, transparent, appropriate, proportionate, and 
[normal]relevant. Equally, we aim to p
[normal]rovide or assist dispute resolution, especially locally, 
[normal]wherever possible and this theme is picked up in our vision which is to "work with 
[normal]others to increase trust in dispute resolution and to improve landlord and tenant 
[normal]relations".
[normal]The primary outcomes o
[normal]f our vision and mission are that, in 2016:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Tenants and landlords have increased trust in dispute resolution;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Tenant and landlord relations are improved;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Landlords have a positive view of complaints;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Designated persons are playing their part in resolving 
[normal]disputes fairly.
[normal]Philosophy:[bold]The changes to my jurisdiction and role as from April 2013 required a consequential 
[normal]revision to our philosophy which is now as follows:
[normal]"In essence, we provide a high quality, impartial service to people who live in, 
[normal]supply, or manage housing. We offer our experience, skills, expertise, and guidance to help tenants, landlords, MPs, councillors, and tenant panels. We
[normal]are not regulators. We are conciliators and problem-solvers. We provide objective solutions at the earli
[normal]est appropriate point. We make a positive 
[normal]contribution to the quality of housing and dispute resolution within the Ombudsman's jurisdiction by:
[normal]a) enabling and encouraging landlords to improve their standards of housing
[normal]management through our independent, 
[normal]impartial, and objective role by:
[normal]- explaining the advantages of complying with our determinations, and 
[normal]- encouraging a positive attitude to the value of the outcomes of complaints and similar feedback
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]helping to improve tenants' individual and shared amenity, environment, 
[normal]and quality of life
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]sharing our expertise, principles, and lessons learnt by highlighting 
[normal]instances of good practice revealed by our process, and
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]supporting good landlord and tenant re
[normal]lations."
[normal]Overall strategic intent:[bold]By achieving our mission, vision, their primary outcomes, and our philosophy we 
[normal]shall realise our overall strategic intent which is to be relevant, make an impact, 
[normal]make a difference, and add value by:
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Being a catalyst for change in the rented-housing sector having fundamentally 
[normal]re-engineered, once again, our dispute resolution process with particular 
[normal]emphasis on the customer's perspective;
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Being the champion of good practice and the source of excellence
[normal] in 
[normal]complaint handling and dispute resolution in rented housing through 
[normal]appropriate and proportionate methods of dissemination;
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Demonstrating that we are making an impact by collecting more data that 
[normal]provide evidence of the success of the measures we shall
[normal] set for 
[normal]organisational performance, service delivery, and monitoring improvement in 
[normal]dispute resolution practice in the sector;
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Applying our resources proportionately to the ombudsman functions of 
[normal]investigation, systemic failures, and knowledge disseminati
[normal]on.
[normal]Developing, improving, and enhancing the following nine characteristics of the value 
[normal]added by our service delivery will make a significant contribution to the success of 
[normal]our strategy:
[normal]i)
[normal]              
[normal]We help improve customer service and positive relationships:
[normal]The outputs of our investigations where service failure or maladministration is found 
[normal]are in the form of recommendations or orders, or both. They may require providers 
[normal]to:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Tell us how they propose to put right the failings we have identified;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Give, or rest
[normal]ore to, residents their entitlements under statute or contract;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Introduce, amend, or properly apply their policies;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Make an apology;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Pay compensation.
[normal]Whether or not we find maladministration our principal aims in composing decisions 
[normal]are to:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Put residents into the position in which they should have been but for their 
[normal]provider's failure;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Enable providers to learn from our findings and apply that learning to the 
[normal]improvement of the quality of the service they provide;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Help 
[normal]improve or sustain a positive relationship between providers and residents;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Contribute to the improvement of customer service.
[normal]ii)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Providers comply with our recommendations and orders:
[normal]There have been very few instances since 1997 in which providers have faile
[normal]d to 
[normal]comply with my recommendations or orders. They recognise, as the Law 
[normal]Commission put it (in their Consultation Paper 196 ) the "political or moral pressure" 
[normal]on them to put things right following a decision of the Ombudsman. They are also confident that
[normal] the Ombudsman is independent and operates an impartial, quality-
[normal]managed process that draws conclusions only from careful analysis of available evidence.
[normal]iii)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We provide advice, assistance, and signposting:
[normal]Even before 1 April 2013 and the re-configuration of our core process to concentrate 
[normal]resources on early dispute resolution, about 90% of cases were already being closed 
[normal]without investigation.
