[normal]iv)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We give an external perspective:
[normal]Often, we 'shine a light' into areas that are obscured from the view of providers. 
[normal]Usually, they accept our findings, acknowledge their failings, and put them right. Even when they may be displeased by the discovery that their systems or 
[normal]management procedures are not as good as they thought they were providers still 
[normal]tend to accept our de
[normal]cisions recognising that they are fair and un-biased and that the 
[normal]Ombudsman has a unique perspective on the way their organisations operate in 
[normal]practice.
[normal]v)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We make 
[normal]'gratis' 
[normal]recommendations:
[normal]Even where we do not make a finding of service failure or maladminist
[normal]ration we 
[normal]sometimes make suggestions to providers for them to consider as part of their customer care and service provision. How they deal with those suggestions is a 
[normal]matter for them but we consider this to be another contribution to the value that we 
[normal]can 
[normal]add to providers and their residents to enrich service provision and customer 
[normal]care.
[normal]vi)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We identify service failure:
[normal]From April 2013 and the operation of the new Scheme, I have been able to make 
[normal]findings not only of maladministration but also service failure. A finding of 
[normal]maladministration or, indeed, severe maladministration will still be available to and 
[normal]will be made in appropriate circumstances but extending the spectrum of 
[normal]maladministration wi
[normal]ll 
[normal]enable findings that would not have merited the strength of 
[normal]criticism evoked by the concept of 'maladministration'. Feedback we have received 
[normal]from providers and other 
[normal]stakeholders indicates that providers are more likely to 
[normal]react with good grace to, and
[normal] residents will, accordingly, benefit from, such findings 
[normal]which can be expressed in more conciliatory and positive terms.
[normal]vii)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We encourage local solutions:
[normal]I now have the power to authorise the drafting of many more orders and 
[normal]recommendations in terms that wil
[normal]l set out the presenting issues and then require 
[normal]providers to design appropriate remedial actions. Again, feedback from providers 
[normal]and other stakeholders during the consultation process that preceded formal 
[normal]approval of my new Scheme, indicated that provider
[normal]s would more likely to be 
[normal]encouraged to take responsibility for resolving disputes and be more likely to 
[normal]produce an outcome that suits local conditions and meets the particular needs of residents especially if providers work with tenant scrutiny panels. We
[normal] are gathering 
[normal]data against which we shall test these assumptions.
[normal]viii)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Under the terms of my Scheme, providers are expected to comply with my 
[normal]determinations. If they do not, I have the power to:
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Require them to report to me on compliance with a determination in such a 
[normal]way and at such a time as I may specify;
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Report them to any appropriate regulatory agency and/or, in accordance with 
[normal]the policy o
[normal]f localism and co-regulation as expressed in the Localism Act, the 
[normal]boards, committees, or tenant scrutiny panels of providers;
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Order them to publish that they have failed to comply, in such a way as I see fit;
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Publish the facts and circumstances of non-compliance naming the providers 
[normal]in my annual report or elsewhere.
[normal]ix)
[normal]              
[normal]We share our learning:
[normal]An important objective of my Service has always been to share lessons learnt not 
[normal]only with landlords but also with other
[normal]s with an interest in the outcomes of our core 
[normal]process. Traditionally, we have done this by publishing reports, speaking at 
[normal]conferences and seminars, and providing training for Board members, front-line staff, and tenants. Landlords, in particular, have fe
[normal]d back to us that these initiatives have 
[normal]helped them to change and to design policies and practices in respect of complaint-
[normal]handling in particular and wider customer service in general. Our historical shared-
[normal]learning 
[normal]inter-actions with providers and residents were so well-valued and 
[normal]respected that we were frequently approached by landlords and landlord and tenant 
[normal]bodies to deliver it for them by special request.
[normal]To deliver our current vision and mission we intend to wo
[normal]rk with landlords and 
[normal]tenants to resolve disputes that come to us impartially using processes that are fair, 
[normal]evidence-based, and free of bias and prejudice. These principles of dispute 
[normal]resolution will be,the basis of 
[normal]our work with landlords, tenants, MPs, 
[normal]councillors, and 
[normal]tenant panels. We are developing an extended set of dispute resolution principles 
[normal]which will be augmented by complementary learning media. Working with all 
[normal]interested parties, we aim to achieve accessible dispute resolution that will be of
[normal] 
[normal]benefit to both landlords and tenants and encourage landlords to use these 
[normal]outcomes to improve the services they provide.
[normal]Governance:[bold]The Housing Act 1996 (Sch. 2., para.10) provides for the Ombudsman's Scheme to 
[normal]be administered by a body corporate or by 
[normal]a corporation sole. Until 1 April 2013 
[normal]there was a body corporate, IHO Limited, a company limited by guarantee and not 
[normal]trading for profit which, in 2006, was designated as an eNDPB. The Board 
[normal]comprised equal numbers of tenants, landlords, and independents 
[normal](the 'constituency 
[normal]model'). The Secretary of State made an order establishing The Housing 
[normal]Ombudsman as a corporation sole. As Ombudsman, Chief Executive, and
[normal] 
[normal]Accounting Officer, I am supported
[normal] by an Audit and Risk Committee. In accordance 
[normal]with an express provision in the Scheme I may set up a Panel of Advisors but such a 
[normal]group is not part of the governance of the corporation sole and advises me 
[normal]personally.
[normal]The principal reasons for changes in g
[normal]overnance were:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To support my independence as Ombudsman in the discharge of my 
[normal]statutory function;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To remove 'double governance';
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To reduce the costs (direct and indirect) of servicing two full governance 
[normal]structures;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To remove the potential for conflict 
[normal]arising from my three roles;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The extension of jurisdiction under the Localism Act 2011;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To reflect my future status as an office holder not an employee.
[normal]I turn now to the specific points raised in your letter. 
[normal]Harmonisation of Ombudsman Schemes [bold]Ease of ac[bold]cess:[bold]Two of the primary outcomes of our mission and vision are that tenants and 
[normal]landlords have increased trust in dispute resolution and designated persons are 
[normal]playing their part in resolving disputes fairly. It is important to understand that, for 
[normal]us, th
[normal]e 'increased trust' refers broadly to dispute resolution in rented housing that 
[normal]may be taking place locally between landlords and tenants or by designated persons as well as when it is escalated to me.
[normal]Achievem
[normal]ent of our strategic intent will deliver better access to dispute resolution for 
[normal]residents.
[normal]Many providers, especially since the coming into force of the Localism Act, have 
[normal]reduced 
[normal]their ICPs to two stages and many do not explicitly refer to 'stages' in an
[normal] attempt to resolve complaints and disputes without raising an expectation that all 
[normal]`stages' must be completed before resolution may be had. Such providers share with 
[normal]us the importance of early, local, appropriate, and proportionate dispute resolution.
[normal]Con[bold]fusion:[bold]My recent experience is that confusion about the ways in which people in my 
[normal]jurisdiction can complain has been caused by two principal factors. The first is the 
[normal]clumsy, complex, and clunky drafting of section 180 of the Localism Act. When I 
[normal]asked a
[normal] leading Housing Law QC for advice on certain aspects of this section one of 
[normal]his observations was that "it is clear that it is unclear". If this is the opinion of a QC 
[normal]landlords and tenants can be forgiven if they too are confused and probably explains why
[normal] myths such as that of the "8-week rule" occur.
[normal]Linked to this is the complete lack of communication by government of the 
[normal]consequences of legislation such as section 180 to people who will be affected by it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are all committed to achieving cost effectiveness and good value for money in 
[normal]these times of economic challenge and austerity but there is a strong case for 
[normal]certain, especially low-cost, exceptions. My Service does not have the resources to 
[normal]mount far-reaching communication exercises. Even if we did, we must seek an 
[normal]exemption from DCLG to spend money from our budget on, for instance, leaflets for 
[normal]tenants. Recently, for example, I put up a business case to spend £6,000 on such 
[normal]leaflets but, in 
[normal]line with Francis Maude's decrees concerning spending on marketing, 
[normal]promotion, and communication, was eventually granted an exemption to spend £4,000.
[normal]Given these systemic limitations on our ability to inform, our strategic approach is to 
[normal]work with others 
[normal](e.g. 
[normal]landlords, trade bodies, and others) to use their networks and 
[normal]resources to reach our customers.
[normal]Fitting alongside others:[bold]In terms of consultation and collaborative working the Localism Act adds the Housing 
[normal]Ombudsman to the list of bodies with whom 
[normal]the Local Government Ombudsmen (LGO) may consult during the course of their investigations. It also provides that if, 
[normal]at any stage in the course of conducting an investigation, I form the opinion that the 
[normal]complaint relates partly to a matter which could be
[normal] the subject of an investigation by 
[normal]the LGO, I must consult with the appropriate 'Commissioner' about the complaint 
[normal]and, if I consider it necessary, inform the complainant of the steps necessary to 
[normal]initiate a complaint with the LGO.
[normal]Provision is also made 
[normal]to enable me and the LGO to carry out joint investigations. In 
[normal]particular, if at any stage in the course of conducting an investigation I form the 
[normal]opinion that the complaint relates partly to a matter within the jurisdiction of the LGO, 
[normal]I [bold]may conduct an investigation jointly with the LGO provided I have first obtained the 
[normal]consent of the complainant or the complainant's representative. Moreover, if I form the opinion that a complaint which is being investigated by the LGO relates partly to 
[normal]a
[normal] matter within my jurisdiction, I may conduct an investigation jointly with the LGO 
[normal]and we may make joint reports so long as we distinguish my determinations from 
[normal]other findings or 
[normal]recommendations.
[normal]I am currently talking to the LGO about a memorandum of un
[normal]derstanding (MOU) that 
[normal]will help us provide a seamless, high quality service to our respective customers for 
[normal]those occasions, should they ever occur, when we might conduct joint investigations. 
[normal]There have not been any since 1 April 2013.
[normal]We do not have an 
[normal]MOU with the PHSO. To my knowledge we have not had a 
[normal]single case in which our jurisdictions have ever overlapped although sometimes 
[normal]people have contacted the PHSO about a matter within my jurisdiction and have 
[normal]been referred by them to me.
[normal]Sharing good prac[bold]tice with other Ombudsmen:[bold]My colleagues and I attend conferences and special interest groups arranged and 
[normal]supported by the Ombudsman Association. Although my predecessor decided to 
[normal]stop attending meetings of the Public Sector Ombudsmen Group because he, l
[normal]ike
[normal] 
[normal]me, considered the Housing Ombudsman to be, predominantly, a private sector ombudsman, I decided to accept Sir Tony Redmond's invitation to attend meetings of the group because I took the view that any opportunity to mix with other 
[normal]ombudsmen to share good 
[normal]practice, challenges, mutual concerns and interests, new 
[normal]developments, and emerging trends was of benefit to my Service.
[normal]My colleagues and I also meet other ombudsman and their colleagues at different 
[normal]levels for different purposes. In recent months, for ex
[normal]ample, I have had meetings with The Property Ombudsman, the Ombudsman (Property), the Pensions Ombudsman and the CEO of The Dispute Service. Colleagues have visited, for 
[normal]example, the Legal Ombudsman to share concerns and ambitions concerning data 
[normal]collectio
[normal]n and processing for accountability, improved organisational performance, 
[normal]and better customer service.
[normal]Single access point:[bold]I am instinctively but cautiously drawn to this concept by the obvious benefits 
[normal]especially to customers if it could be organised eff
[normal]ectively and efficiently. During the course of my nearly 13 years as an ombudsman I have been to many meetings in 
[normal]different 
[normal]fora 
[normal]to discuss the implementation of a 'single portal'. It remains, however, 
[normal]something of the 'holy grail' of ombudsmanry.
[normal]My conce
[normal]rns are:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Will it deliver my strategic aims and their primary outcomes?
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How is it going to be paid for?
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Will that be more expensive than my present arrangements that have been 
[normal]put in place following the fundamental review of our core process and role?
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What 
[normal]control will 
[normal]I [bold]have over the quality of service provision?
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What would be my rights to withdraw from such a service if it wasn't working 
[normal]to my satisfaction and to deliver my strategic aims?
[normal]Single PSOE:[bold]A single PSOE appears, superficially, to be a good thing but, from my point of view, it 
[normal]is another myth that has emerged from the mists of prejudice and assumption. To my knowledge it has never be subjected to what the judges call "nice chemical 
[normal]analysis".
[normal]Before I could support this idea I should need to be convinced by:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clearly set out aims, objectives, and outcomes;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A clearly set out, argued rationale as to why it would be an improvement on 
[normal]where we are now;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A cost-benefit analysis;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An options appraisal;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An audit of necessary changes to primary legislation;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An informed and authoritative assessment of the likelihood of legislative 
[normal]changes and a clear indication of timescales;
[normal]• A comprehensive risk assessment.
[normal]I have had brief conversations with Julie Mellor and Jane Martin about this issue. I have made it clear to both that compelling evidence from the combination of the 
[normal]above list would be a 
[normal]sine qua non 
[normal]of my decision to support or not support the idea 
[normal]of a P
[normal]SOE. At my last meeting with Julie I made it clear that in the absence of such 
[normal]evidence I would not be able to form a considered view of the concept.
[normal]European Directive in Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR)[bold]What consideration have you given to the introduction of the Directive and are [bold]you taking any action in response?[bold]"Appropriate/alternative"[bold]Although I get the point that the proposal applies to ADR that seeks to resolve 
[normal]disputes between consumers and trade
[normal]rs "out-of-court" it is a pity that the Directive 
[normal]defines ADR as 
[normal]Alternative 
[normal]Dispute Resolution rather than 
[normal]Appropriate 
[normal]because 
[normal]courts are sometimes the only 'appropriate' forum for the resolution of a dispute 
[normal](e.g. 
[normal]novel points of law, interpretation of t
[normal]he law, where remedies such as damages, 
[normal]injunction and specific performance are sought).
[normal]Common principles[bold]The Directive states that effective ADR procedures should be guided by a number of 
[normal]common principles, such as impartiality, transparency, effectivene
[normal]ss, and fairness. 
[normal]No ombudsman in the UK or Ireland will disagree with this statement except to say 
[normal]that the criteria set out by the Ombudsman Association (OA) for membership in the 
[normal]`ombudsman' category might go further than these criteria. The Cabinet off
[normal]ice and the Ministry of Justice have formally accepted and endorsed OA's extended criteria 
[normal]which are included in their joint guidance to government departments which are 
[normal]thinking of reviewing or setting up ombudsman schemes.
[normal]Cross-border complaints[bold]The int
[normal]ention of the Commission is to propose measures on ADR that ensure that all 
[normal]consumer complaints can be submitted to an ADR entity and that disputes arising from cross-border transactions and the digital environment may be more easily 
[normal]resolved. On the basis
[normal] of past experience, I do not expect my Service to be involved 
[normal]in any cross-border transaction in the terms of the proposal.
[normal]Digital environment[bold]The digital environment is of relevance to my Service and we plan further to develop 
[normal]our website but also to cr
[normal]eate a digital media communication strategy that will help 
[normal]us raise awareness of our services and also to enable easier and wider access to them. We acknowledge government's aspiration to achieve 'digital by default' and 
[normal]are seeking to work with others to overcome significant challenges facing residents 
[normal]in my jurisdiction to achieve it. Many, for instance, cannot afford telephone land lines 
[normal]and therefore have no access to broadband and the internet. Many others are
[normal] 
[normal]denied digital facilities by reason of their advanced age, ill-health and other frailty, or 
[normal]special needs.
[normal]The Directive will require Member States to ensure that all disputes between a 
[normal]consumer and a trader arising from the sale of 
[normal]goods or the provision of services can 
[normal]be submitted to an ADR entity, including through online means. Subject to the 
[normal]challenges referred to above, our new website is designed to be inter-active and, I 
[normal]believe, would already meet the Commission's requiremen
[normal]t.
[normal]Enhanced redress[bold]The second objective of the Directive to enhance redress for consumers is directly 
[normal]relevant to one of the aspects of my role but I cannot presently see how the Directive 
[normal]will actually enhance redress for residents, landlords, and managing agents in my 
[normal]jurisdiction.
[normal]Lack of awareness and uneven quality[bold]The Directive recounts that analysis of the current situation identified certain main 
[normal]shortcomings which hinder the effectiveness of ADR such as the lack of consumer 
[normal]and business awareness, and the uneven quality of ADR procedures.
[normal]Within the limits placed on us by government in terms of communicating to our customers, we shall continue to 
[normal]do all we can raise awareness of our Service. In 
[normal]particular we shall use our new website and will continue to work with landlords and 
[normal]their professional and trade bodies and with tenant organisations to get across 
[normal]messages about who we are, what we do, and
[normal] how we add value.
[normal]I am not in a position to comment on whether there is uneven quality of ADR 
[normal]procedures in the context of rented housing. I can say, however, that the quality of 
[normal]my Service has been consistently recognised and reflected in objective and 
[normal]u
[normal]nsolicited evidence.
[normal]Residual cross-sectoral entity[bold]Apart from my comments about private-for-profit landlords and managing agents being required to join my Scheme, I presently have no views on a residual cross
[normal]&#xad;
[normal]sectoral 
[normal]entity.
[normal]Complaints filed by traders a[bold]gainst consumers[bold]The Commission's proposal covers disputes between consumers and traders (the 
[normal]latter being defined as "any natural persons or any legal person, irrespective of 
[normal]whether privately or publicly owned, who is acting, including through any person
[normal] 
[normal]acting in his name or on his behalf, for purposes relating to his trade, business, craft 
[normal]or profession arising from the sale of goods or the provision of services") and 
[normal]includes complaints filed by consumers against traders as well as complaints filed by 
[normal]traders against consumers. In the context of the Housing Ombudsman and assuming 
[normal]that the definition of "trader" includes landlords, there would have to be a change in 
[normal]primary legislation to allow landlords to trigger disputes coming to me.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Accessible information about ADR providers [bold]The proposal states:
[normal]"When disputes arise, consumers must be able to quickly identify which ADR 
[normal]entities are competent to deal with their dispute. To this end, this proposal 
[normal]ensures that consumers will be able to find information on the competent ADR entity in the main commercial documents provided by the trader and, where a 
[normal]trader has a website, on that website. In addition, traders will have to inform 
[normal]consumers on whether or
[normal] not they commit to use ADR in relation to 
[normal]complaints lodged against them by a consumer. This obligation will act as an 
[normal]incentive for traders to use ADR more frequently."
[normal]To the 
[normal]extent that "traders" includes landlords in my jurisdiction, these criteria are met. Some landlords even make clear in their tenancy agreements residents' rights 
[normal]to escalate disputes. If for-profit private-sector landlords and managing agents were 
[normal]required
[normal] to join my Scheme as a result of the Directive, I have the power in the 
[normal]approved Scheme to require the same criteria of them.
[normal]Costs, length, and complexity[bold]I am confident that the fundamental changes we have made recently to our 
[normal]procedures and practices i
[normal]ncluding, especially, our re-engineered core dispute 
[normal]resolution process and strategic re-alignment of resources linked to an activity-based 
[normal]costing model will meet the following requirement of the Commission's proposal:
[normal]`ADR procedures should be effective 
[normal]and address certain shortcomings 
[normal]associated with court procedures, such as costs, length and complexity."
[normal]Resolution within 90 days[bold]Since we have re-aligned our resources to deliver early local dispute resolution we 
[normal]are completing cases in minutes, days, o
[normal]r weeks and would expect in the majority of 
[normal]cases to satisfy the Commission's requirement that:
[normal]" Based on the results of existing studies, the present proposal requires that 
[normal]disputes should be resolved within 90 days."
[normal]The addition of the word "generally" later in the text satisfies me that 90 days is a 
[normal]desirable rather than an absolute and permits flexibility and discretion to produce a 
[normal]just outcome in appropriate cases such as, for instance, novel or complex cases, 
[normal]ins
[normal]tances involving systemic issues, or matters containing important learning 
[normal]outcomes for the sector or in the public interest.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Free of charge[bold]The proposal states that:
[normal]"In order to ensure that ADR procedures remain accessible to all 
[normal]consumers,
[normal]the present proposal provides that they should be free of charge or of 
[normal]moderate cost for consumers."
[normal]The services of my organisation are free to residents at the point of complaint. 
[normal]Competent authorities[bold]It is proposed that, in each Member State
[normal], a competent authority will be in charge of monitoring the functioning of ADR entities established on its territory. The competent authorities will, 
[normal]inter alia, 
[normal]assess, on the basis of information notified to them by ADR 
[normal]entities, whether a given ADR enti
[normal]ty respects the quality requirements laid down by the present proposal.
[normal]It is not clear to me how such an arrangement would align with my existing duty 
[normal]under statute to report annually to the Secretary of State who lays the report before 
[normal]Parliament. If it 
[normal]means double reporting there will be an unnecessarily bureaucratic 
[normal]process and a risk that resources that would be better directed to providing an improved service to consumers will be needlessly spent on duplication.
[normal]It seems to me that where reports are 
[normal]laid before Parliament they are documents of 
[normal]public record and this requirement should be enough to meet the requirements of the 
[normal]Directive. Equally, the public availability of such reports should be enough to enable:
[normal]" the competent authorities to publish regular reports on the development and 
[normal]functioning of ADR entities. Every three years, the Commission will report to 
[normal]the European Parliament and the Council on the application of the Directive".
[normal]To what extent do you [bold]believe the Directive will allow better and meaningful [bold]comparisons in performance and sharing of practice across providers or agencies?[bold]I do not believe that the Directive will allow better comparisons in performance. Ombudsmen in the UK, for instance, hav
[normal]e tried in a variety of networking 
[normal]fora 
[normal]to 
[normal]make 
[normal]such comparisons but their constitutional arrangements, core processes, and 
[normal]related performance measures, or KPIs, or targets are so disparate that comparison 
[normal]inevitably fails to get apples and pears to coinc
[normal]ide.
[normal]Subject to my fears of duplication and unnecessary costs referred to above, I do 
[normal]believe, however, that "competent authorities" and the collation of reporting 
[normal]mechanisms by the Commission to the European Parliament will provide the 
[normal]potential for a fra
[normal]mework to facilitate sharing of good practice.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]To what extent do you think the Directive presents an opportunity to remodel [bold]the existing system of ADR to resolve possible existing overlaps, shortfalls, [bold]and conflicts?[bold]The Directive states that another of the main shortcomings which hinders the 
[normal]effectiveness of ADR is "gaps in the coverage". The most obvious gap in terms of 
[normal]my jurisdiction is the fact that the vast majority of consumers of services provided by 
[normal]private, f
[normal]or-profit landlords and managing agents are excluded from access to my 
[normal]Service, and, therefore, justice, in respect of unsatisfactory provision of those 
[normal]services for which they pay market rents. These consumers have for too long been 
[normal]the Cinderellas at the
[normal] ADR ball. Government strongly supports the role of the private 
[normal]sector in the provision of rented housing. Giving tenants in this sector the right to 
[normal]escalate their disputes to the Housing Ombudsman would not only give them the 
[normal]rights of access to ADR requ
[normal]ired by the Directive and thereby access to out-of-court 
[normal]justice but would also test standards in that sector and drive up the quality of 
[normal]customer service by reference to an ever-increasing body of learning arising out of a 
[normal]rich bank of ombudsman decision-
[normal]outcomes.
[normal]How can those involved in dispute resolution, but who aren't covered by the Directive, ensure that they are meeting the same expected standards of quality [bold]as those who are covered by it?[bold]As stated above, Ombudsman members of OA will not have diff
[normal]iculty meeting the 
[normal]standards. Indeed, many of us, no doubt, will be able to argue that we exceed them.
[normal]I suspect that the simple answer to this question is that those who are not covered 
[normal]by the Directive should ensure, by amendment and revision if necessar
[normal]y, that their 
[normal]constitutional arrangements meet the standards. This will be a matter, as may be 
[normal]appropriate, for their Boards, councils, regulators, departmental sponsors, industry 
[normal]stakeholders, and, ultimately, government.
[normal]How can the government ensure aga[bold]inst the proliferation of excessive [bold]numbers of different dispute resolution bodies and mechanisms (and should it [bold]be doing so)?[bold]This is definitely something in respect of which the government should be taking a 
[normal]lead. The proliferation of different ombudsmen and other dispute resolution bodies 
[normal]in the same or similar industries, sectors, or businesses is very confusing to consumers and does not 
[normal]serve them well in terms of straightforward access to 
[normal]justice.
[normal]Governme
[normal]nt should ensure that the OA guidance endorsed by the Cabinet Office 
[normal]and the Ministry of Justice is followed by its departments. One valuable contribution 
[normal]to this outcome would be that all legislation setting up or reviewing ombudsmen or 
[normal]other ADR schemes 
[normal]should be subject to a pre-condition of approval by Cabinet 
[normal]Office advised by Treasury Solicitors.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Specific action[bold]I have decided not to take any immediate action in response to the Directive 
[normal]principally because I cannot see any obvious impact on my Service particularly in the 
[normal]context of efforts to "improve the functioning of the retail internal market".
[normal]For the moment, I have decided to keep in close contact with fellow ombudsmen, especially t
[normal]hose in the private sector, and monitor how the introduction of the 
[normal]Directive develops and take any action as may be necessary.
[normal]Given that my Service's mission is "impartial dispute resolution for the whole rented sector", I shall be alert to any opportuni
[normal]ty afforded by the Directive to argue that the 
[normal]whole of the rented housing sector (including the private, for-profit sector) should be included in my jurisdiction.
